THE OX ROCKS. Set on a corner of a scruffy commercial strip and a residential street of gentrifying Victorians and century-old shade trees, the Ox Cart does the chalkboard-menu and dinged-furniture thing like many other neighborhood eateries in Brooklyn. But the Ox earns its stars with its food and drink and the professionalism in place since ownership changed in 2017. The staff is mellow and attentive, the specials hearty and flavorful, and the lamb lasagna on the everyday menu worth a three-block walk any snowy night. Prices are moderate, and the televisions tuned to sports are two too many in a tight serving space. Cocktails a strong point.
